schen Prophetie für die alttestamentliche Forschung -- tBiblical Prophecy from a Near Eastern Perspective: The Cases of Kingship and Divine Possession -- tComparing Prophetic Sources: Principles and a Test Case -- tFrom Holy War to Holy Peace: Biblical Alternatives to Belligerent Rhetoric -- tFalsche Prophetie in neuassyrischer und deuteronomistischer Darstellung -- tSacred Springs and Liminal Rivers: Water and Prophecy in the Ancient Eastern Mediterranean -- tProphets and the Divine Council -- tWisdom as Mediatrix in Sirach 24: Ben Sira, Love Lyrics, and Prophecy -- tPart Four: Prophecy in the Hebrew Bible -- tThe Historical Dilemma of Biblical Prophetic Studies -- tSince When Do Prophets Write? -- tProphets and Prophecy in Joshua–Kings: A Near Eastern Perspective -- tDas Problem der Prophetenschüler -- tThe Dubious Image of Prophecy -- t(How) Does the Book of Ezekiel Reveal Its Babylonian Context? -- tThe Book of Hosea and the Last Days of the Northern Kingdom: The Methodological Problem -- tPart Five: Prophecy in the Dead Sea Scrolls -- tTransmitting Divine Mysteries: The Prophetic Role of Wisdom Teachers in the Dead Sea Scrolls -- tOracles at Qumran? Traces of Inspired Speakers in the Dead Sea Scrolls -- tPesharim as Divination: Qumran Exegesis, Omen Interpretation and Literary Prophecy -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of modern authors -- tIndex of Ancient Near Eastern Sources -- tIndex of Biblical References0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProphecy was a wide-spread phenomenon in the ancient world - not only in ancient Israel but in the whole Eastern Mediterranean cultural sphere. This is demonstrated by documents from the ancient Near East, that have been the object of Martti Nissinen’s research for more than twenty years. Nissinen's studies have had a formative influence on the study of the prophetic phenomenon. The present volume presents a selection of thirty-one essays, bringing together essential aspects of prophetic divination in the ancient Near East. The first section of the volume discusses prophecy from theoretical perspectives. The second sections contains studies on prophecy in texts from Mari and Assyria and other cuneiform sources. The third section discusses biblical prophecy in its ancient Near Eastern context, while the fourth section focuses on prophets and prophecy in the Hebrew Bible/Old Testament. Even prophecy in the Dead Sea Scrolls is discussed in the fifth section. The articles are essential reading for anyone studying ancient prophetic phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aProphecyvComparative studies. 0aProphecyxHistory. 0aProphetszMiddle EastxHistory. 0aSemitesxReligion. 4aProphezeiung. 4aReligionsgeschichte. 4aWeissagung. 4ahebräische Bibel. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aDivination.  aHebrew Bible.  aHistory of Religion.  aProphecy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2019z978311071956708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig. Stud., Jewish Stud.2019 Englishz978311061074108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2019z9783110606508oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies De Gruyterz97831107168250 cEPUBz97831104676660 cprintz978311046654640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110